The speckled worm-eel,  Myrophis punctatus, is a member of the Ophichthidae (snake eel) family. It was described by Christian Frederik LÃ¼tken in 1852. M. punctatus have brown bodies that are lighter on the ventral side than the dorsal side.  The upper body is speckled with pepper-like black spots.  The snout is pointed. This species has regenerative powers. They grow to a maximum size of 35.3 centimetres (1.16 ft).